\f2\b \cf0 -
\f1\b0  
\f2\b All Notifications
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\li1080\fi360\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Growl maintains a list of all the notifications that each application supports.\
\pard\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\li1080\fi-360\ql\qnatural

\f2\b \cf0 - Default Notifications\
	
\f1\b0 This is the list of notifications that are enabled by default for an application. This list is maintained persisitently, and separately from the list of allowed notifications.\

\f2\b - Allowed Notifications
\f1\b0 \
	This is the list of all notifications that are actually enabled for an individual application. This will eventually be user-customizable in the preference pane. \

\f2\b - "Use Default"\

\f1\b0 	This is an internal flag within Growl stored for applications. If it is set, it means that the application should keep the Allowed Notification list synced to the Default list, and that it does not reflect any custom preferences.\

\f2\b - Notification Name
\f1\b0 \
	This is an internal name for notifications passed to Growl, never seen by the user. It is passed to 
\f3\fs20 -[NSDistributedObjectCenter \CocoaLigature0 postNotificationName:]
\f1\fs24 \CocoaLigature1 . As it is used in notifications passed all across the system, these names should usually be "namespaced" to an application, typically by prepending some form of the application's name to it, i.e. "
\f3\fs20 Adium-ContactOnline
\f1\fs24 ".\

\f2\b - Notification Title, and Notification Description\

\f1\b0 	These are the user-visible components of each notification, which will actually be displayed by the active notification plugin when an application sends Growl a notification.\
\
